data.title: Asteroid-World Winter 1993-1994
data.text:
Mark Pottenger

Asteroid Ephemerides

Any reader of The Mutable Dilemma and Asteroid-World knows we use a lot of asteroids. However, there are many more we have never looked at. As of the most recent Minor Planet Circulars before the date I am writing this, there are 5,856 numbered asteroids, of which 4,618 are named. New asteroid numbers are assigned continuously, and batches of new names are published every few months. The bulk of this issue of Asteroid-World is a complete list of named asteroids. I recommend the book Dictionary of Minor Planet Names by Lutz D. Schmadel (published by Springer-Verlag) as a somewhat expensive but very complete listing of asteroid name origins.

Eleanor Bach gave astrology the first asteroid ephemeris I am aware of in the early 1970s, with somewhat rounded positions for Ceres, Pallas, Juno and Vesta. (She hired a programmer for the calculation work.) Our family got involved very soon after that. My brother Rique developed the programs necessary to produce the more accurate TIA ephemeris of Ceres, Pallas, Juno and Vesta by working for several months in 1975 on Neil Michelsen’s minicomputer. That work also let Rique add accurate positions for those four asteroids to the 1975 version of the CCRS Horoscope Program.

In the late 1970s, I started developing programs to calculate asteroid ephemerides on our home computers. The first BASIC programs on the S-100 computer we had at that time took days to calculate one century of ephemeris for one asteroid. I converted the programs to the C language in the early 1980s because that was the first language we could get that would take advantage of 8087 math coprocessors. This sped up calculations, but they were still slow. Each new generation of CPU and math coprocessor has sped up the process, until with a 486DX2/66 processor it takes less than 30 seconds to calculate a century of ephemeris for one main-belt asteroid. (On a Pentium, the time would be roughly half that.)

My programs to create ephemerides work by a technique called numerical integration. You start on a date for which you have a well-defined position and velocity for the asteroid of interest and all other bodies in the solar system which might exert any effect on its motion. Calculate all the forces at that moment to predict the position of the asteroid a short time later (or earlier). The time intervals I use range from 1/2 day to 10 days, depending on the asteroid orbit. Repeat all the force calculations at the new date to predict the next position. Continue this process for the whole time interval for which you want an ephemeris. This technique is ideal for creating ephemerides and totally unsuitable for doing individual charts since you can’t get from the starting date to any other date without calculating all the steps between. Since asteroid orbits are heavily perturbed, this is also almost the only way to get reliable asteroid ephemerides.

Starting in 1984, our programs to create asteroid ephemerides were fast enough that we started on a long term campaign to investigate any asteroid with an interesting name. (The astronomer who discovers an asteroid has the right to name it. Names include mythical figures, modern scientists, famous people in many fields, family members, pets, cities, geographic regions, etc. The fun comes in putting an asteroid in a chart in which its name should be relevant and seeing whether it provides meaningful information.) We initially worked with only a few, including those picked by a study group in New York. Gradually, as we thought of other asteroids to look at and other people asked us to calculate still more, we built up a library of ephemerides.

We started making disk ephemerides and the programs to read them available to other people in 1986. After the first few sets I set a price to sell them. In 1988, to be able to have some sort of standard package for orders, I established all 453 ephemerides we had done to that date as a standard set and worked up documentation for where most of the names came from. Any ephemerides added after that date were treated as a library that people could order from piecemeal. By late 1993, the standard set plus the library included a total of almost 2,500 asteroids.

However, there is a drawback to those ephemerides. They only cover one century, and we are fast approaching the end of the century. I was reluctant to extend the ephemerides, both because of disk space (they already took up about 30 Megabytes) and because every ephemeris I calculated still involved several manual steps in addition to the actual calculation time on the computer.

Rob Hand and I discussed the issue of asteroid ephemerides over a year ago, and agreed on a new format we might both support. (Considering how many megabytes ephemerides can fill, we thought it would be a good idea to avoid duplicate sets caused by software differences.) Based on preliminary work Rob did, we estimated that this new format should let us store ephemerides almost twice as efficiently as I had been doing. Since the beginning of this year, I have been doing the actual implementation based on our discussion. In practice, some of our original ideas had to be modified, but I am now able to generate ephemerides covering the years 1900-2099 that take up only a little more space than the previous one-century ephemerides.

My new programs now automate several steps I was doing separately before. The orbit is calculated from multiple starting points (currently four, with room for more when I can get more files of elements). Each set of calculations is checked against observations, and the best match is kept. (In the few cases where I have no observations to check against, I simply use the most recently published starting elements.) Orbital elements are determined from the positions calculated during the numerical integration. The orbital elements are tested over a series of widening intervals to see how frequently they need to be stored to retain accuracy. Depending on the interval between elements found necessary for adequate accuracy, a final ephemeris using either XYZ positions or elements is created. The process of testing for the best storage interval actually can take longer than the original integration.

I am pleased to finally be able to report a milestone: we now have disk ephemerides for 4,617 named asteroids (all currently named asteroids except lost 719 Albert and lost unnumbered Hermes). The new ephemerides for the years 1900-2099 take up about 54 Megabytes of disk space. Within a week or two, I expect to finish the calculations to extend all of those ephemerides back to 1500. We will finally be able to work with any named asteroid just by taking it from the new library. Now the only problem is how to pick and choose!
